---
import PostLayout from '../../layouts/PostLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/?$/, '/');

const title = 'Windows 98 Nostalgia: We Built a Game That Takes Programmers Back to the 90s — DUX Games';
const description = 'A free nostalgic clicker sim about the journey from machine code to the modern AI & Cloud era, built in the style of old-school computer interfaces.';
const canonical = 'https://mrsanchezzzzz.github.io/dux-games/posts/wincode-98-nostalgia/';
const ogImage = 'https://mrsanchezzzzz.github.io/dux-games/assets/posts/wincode-98/cover.webp';
const jsonLd = JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "Windows 98 Nostalgia: We Built a Game That Takes Programmers Back to the 90s",
  "description": "A free nostalgic clicker sim about the journey from machine code to the modern AI & Cloud era, built in the style of old-school computer interfaces.",
  "image": "https://mrsanchezzzzz.github.io/dux-games/assets/posts/wincode-98/cover.webp",
  "datePublished": "2026-06-20",
  "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "DUX Games", "url": "https://mrsanchezzzzz.github.io/dux-games/" },
  "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "DUX Games", "url": "https://mrsanchezzzzz.github.io/dux-games/" },
  "url": "https://mrsanchezzzzz.github.io/dux-games/posts/wincode-98-nostalgia/"
});
---
<PostLayout
  {title}
  {description}
  {canonical}
  {ogImage}
  publishedTime="2026-06-20"
  tags={["WinCode 98", "indie game", "clicker game"]}
  category="Devlog"
  date="June 20, 2026"
  {jsonLd}
>
  <Fragment slot="hero">
    <a class="back" href={`${base}#journal`}><span class="back-arrow">←</span> Journal</a>
    <div class="post-meta">
      <span class="cat">Devlog</span>
      <span class="date">June 20, 2026</span>
    </div>
    <h1>Windows 98 Nostalgia: We Built a Game That Takes Programmers Back to the 90s</h1>
    <p class="lede">A free nostalgic clicker sim about the journey from machine code to the modern AI&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Cloud era, built in the style of old-school computer interfaces.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <p>We built <strong>WinCode 98</strong> — a free programmer clicker sim styled after old-school computer interfaces.</p>

  <p>It's a game for people who love code, retro aesthetics, idle/clicker games, and that feeling of slow, satisfying progress. We didn't want to make just another clicker — we wanted to capture the atmosphere of the 90s: grey windows, pixel buttons, plain menus, system alerts, and that exact mood of an old computer.</p>

  <figure class="post-img">
    <img src={`${base}assets/posts/wincode-98/cover.webp`} alt="WinCode 98 main screen" />
  </figure>

  <p>In WinCode 98, the player follows a programmer's journey from the very beginning all the way to the modern AI&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Cloud era. The core mechanic clicks into place within seconds: tap to write code, earn money from projects, buy upgrades, and level up your programmer across 5 technology eras.</p>

  <p>But progress in the game isn't just bigger numbers. Each new era feels like the next step in the history of programming.</p>

  <figure class="post-img phone">
    <img src={`${base}assets/posts/wincode-98/write-code.webp`} alt="WinCode 98 main gameplay screen" />
  </figure>

  <h2>5 Eras of Programming History</h2>

  <ul class="era-list cols">
    <li><strong>Machine Era</strong> <span>the beginning: raw commands and machine-level thinking.</span></li>
    <li><strong>Procedural Era</strong> <span>the age of functions, algorithms, and structured code.</span></li>
    <li><strong>OOP Era</strong> <span>classes, objects, architecture, and more complex projects.</span></li>
    <li><strong>Internet Era</strong> <span>the web, servers, networks, and online products.</span></li>
    <li><strong>AI &amp; Cloud Era</strong> <span>the modern stage: cloud tech, automation, and artificial intelligence.</span></li>
  </ul>

  <figure class="post-img phone">
    <img src={`${base}assets/posts/wincode-98/travel-tech-eras.webp`} alt="WinCode 98 first and last era collage" />
  </figure>

  <h2>Upgrades, Projects, and Random Events</h2>

  <p>To keep the run from feeling repetitive, the game includes upgrades, projects, and random events. Upgrades help you grow faster. Projects open up new possibilities.</p>

  <p>Random events keep things dynamic. Sometimes a client leaves a tip, giving the player a welcome bonus. Other times a challenge appears that needs solving — pull it off and you'll earn a reward that accelerates your programmer's growth.</p>

  <p>Because programming isn't always a straight line. Sometimes everything works on the first try. Sometimes there's a bug. Sometimes an unexpected event changes the whole pace of the game.</p>

  <div class="post-img-pair">
    <figure class="post-img phone">
      <img src={`${base}assets/posts/wincode-98/unlock-&-boost.webp`} alt="WinCode 98 upgrades screen" />
    </figure>
    <figure class="post-img phone">
      <img src={`${base}assets/posts/wincode-98/solve-challenges.webp`} alt="WinCode 98 random event screen" />
    </figure>
  </div>

  <h2>Retro Style Inspired by the 90s</h2>

  <p>Visually, we designed WinCode 98 in a retro style inspired by late-90s interfaces. We wanted the game to look like something you could have found on an old computer — but still feel comfortable for a modern player.</p>

  <p>WinCode 98 is free to play. We want as many players as possible to try it, walk the path from Machine Era to AI&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Cloud, and soak in the nostalgic atmosphere of an old computer.</p>

  <figure class="post-img phone">
    <img src={`${base}assets/posts/wincode-98/promo.webp`} alt="WinCode 98 — Free on release, Coming soon on App Store" />
  </figure>

  <p>WinCode 98 is worth trying if you're a programmer, or anyone who loves clicker games, retro computers, and the story of how technology evolved.</p>

  <Fragment slot="footer-nav">
    <a class="back" href={`${base}#journal`}>← All posts</a>
  </Fragment>
</PostLayout>
